e Hood]] and [[Timbaland]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Wild Thoughts\" <small>(produced with [[Party Next Door]], and [[DJ Khaled]])</small>\n| rowspan=2 | 2017\n| [[DJ Khaled]] featuring [[Rihanna]] and [[Bryson Tiller]]\n| rowspan=2 | ''[[Grateful (DJ Khaled album)|Grateful]]''\n|-\n|}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090106062610/http://www.ozonemag.com/jun2004/text-nastybeatmakers.html Article in ''Ozone'' magazine]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090225234848/http://www.purecashmagazine.com/2008/07/16/nasty-beatmakers/ Interview in ''Pure Cash'' magazine]\n\n{{Cash Money Records}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dj Nasty and Lvm}}\n[[Category:American hip hop record producers]]\n[[Category:American musical duos]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Florida]]\n[[Category:Cash Money Records artists]]\n[[Category:Family musical groups]]\n[[Category:Hip hop duos]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Florida]]\n[[Category:Record production duos]]\n[[Category:Sibling musical duos]]\n[[Category:Southern hip hop musicians]]\n[[Category:African-American record producers]]\n", "text_old": "{{no footnotes|date=December 2012}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n|name            = NastyBeatmakers \n|image             =\n|caption        = \n|image_size        =\n|background      = group_or_band\n|alias           = Nasty Beatmakers\n|birth_date      =\n|origin          = [[Orlando, Florida|Orlando]], [[Florida]], United States\n|instrument      = [[Yamaha Motif]], [[Apple GarageBand]], [[Music Production Center|Akai MPC4000]], [[Novation DrumStation]], [[Roland MC-808]]\n|genre           = [[Hip hop music|Hip hop Reggaeton]]\n|occupation      = [[record producer|Record production team|]]\n|years_active    = 1999-present\n|label           = [[We The Best]]\n|associated_acts = [[DJ Khaled]], [[Rick Ross]], [[Fat Joe]]\n|website             =\n|current_members = *DJ Nasty\n*LVM\n|past_members    =\n}}\n\n'''NastyBeatmakers''' are an American Grammy Award winning record production duo, composed of brothers '''DJ Nasty''' (Johnny David Mollings) and '''LVM''' (Leonardo V. Mollings). With decades in the industry and a plethora of accolades under their belt, they cover a vast array of genres in the music industry. When DJ Nasty is not touring with the likes of [[Jay-Z]], [[Beyonce]], [[DJ Khaled]] or [[Fat Joe]], he is a DJ at the biggest celebrity parties and on the radio in [[Orlando]]. LVM is a well-trained musician who has toured with [[SNAP]] & [[Backstreet Boys]] & has played guitar on [[DJ Khaled]]'s [[Wild Thoughts]]. LVM and DJ Nasty also produced DJ Khaled's [[All I Do is Win]] and [[Wild Thoughts]] along with being a part of a list of other songs from other top musicians, including DJ Khaled, [[Lil Wayne]], [[Rick Ross]], [[Plies (rapper)|Plies]], [[Ludacris]], [[Young Jeezy]], [[Flo Rida]], [[Rick Ross (rapper)|Rick Ross]], [[Birdman (rapper)|Birdman]], [[8Ball & MJG]], [[Juelz Santana]], [[Cam'Ron]], [[Fat Joe]], [[Pitbull (rapper)|Pitbull]] and [[Chingy]]. Their major influences in producing come from [[The Neptunes]], [[Pete Rock]], [[The Runners]], and [[Dr. Dre]].\n\nContinuing to produce and having an influence on today's latest music, the duo takes time to mentor artists and up and coming producers in the industry. They have also showcased their creative juices into other ventures in the music industry and beyond. With a unique mix of live guitar strings being played by LVM while his brother DJ Nasty mixes at the DJ Booth, the duo has performed live on many occasions for fans and partners.  \n\nThrough the years some of Hip Hops biggest songs have come from the duo with favorites over the years such as [[Lil Wayne]]'s \"[[I'm Me]]\", [[Plies (rapper)|Plies]]'s \"#1 Fan\", featuring [[J. Holiday]] and [[Keyshia Cole]] and their Grammy Produced [[Ludacris]]'s \"[[Grew Up A Screw Up]]\", featuring [[Young Jeezy]], \n\n==History==\n===Early life and career beginnings===\nDJ Nasty and LVM were both born in [[Cuba]], and came to the United States in 1988 due to their father being in the [[United States Navy|Navy]]; he \"wanted a change in scenery\", states Nasty.  DJ Nasty early on met [[DJ Khaled]] and another associate named Ceaser and started Hitmen Productions. They were doing local house parties and renting out halls, and soon started to make a big name for themselves in [[Orlando, Florida|Orlando]], [[Florida]]. The group eventually broke up due to [[DJ Khaled]] moving to [[New Orleans]], [[Louisiana]], with his parents because they owned a clothing store there. Today, Khaled and Ceaser are still good friends with Nasty. DJ Nasty & DJ Khaled have a management company \"We The Best Management\" which houses the super producers [[The Runners]].\n\nDJ Nasty's first track was actually [[Krayzie Bone]]'s \"Thug Alwayz\" on Krayzie's ''[[Thug Mentality 1999]]'' (1999). But DJ Nasty is not too fond of that record, and actually considers the beat he did for [[Fat Joe]] \"The Wild Life\" to be his true first track. LVM started out doing a record for [[95 South]] called \"Cheer For Me\" which can be heard on the ''Bring It On'' soundtrack, as well as numerous remixes for the likes of [[Jordan Knight]] and [[Shaquille O'Neal]]. LVM dabbled in the pop market producing \"Baby Be Mine\" for pop group [[LFO]].\n\nSuccess started to take off when DJ Nasty befriended [[Disturbing tha Peace|DTP]]'s Co-CEO Chaka Zulu and landed a few placements with [[Ludacris]] in 2003 for his ''[[Chicken-n-Beer]]'' album's \"Southern Fried Intro\".\n\n\n==Discography==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" border=\"1\"\n|-\n! Song\n! Year\n! Artist(s)\n! Album\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Thug Alwayz\" <small>(produced with Rater)</small>\n| 1999\n| [[Krayzie Bone]] featuring [[Bone Thugs-n-Harmony]]\n| ''[[Thug Mentality 1999]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"The Wild Life\"\n| 2001\n| [[Fat Joe]] featuring Prospect and [[Xzibit]]\n| ''[[Jealous Ones Still Envy (J.O.S.E.)]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Smokin' Dro\"\n| rowspan=2 | 2002\n| [[Disturbing tha Peace]] featuring [[2 Chainz|Tity Boi]], [[I-20]] and [[Ludacris]]\n| ''[[Golden Grain]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"[[Tell Me (Smilez and Southstar song)|Tell Me]]\"\n| [[Smilez and Southstar]]\n| ''[[Crash the Party]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Southern Fried Intro\"\n| rowspan=2 | 2003\n| [[Ludacris]]\n| rowspan=2 | ''[[Chicken-n-Beer]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Hard Times\"\n| [[Ludacris]] featuring [[8Ball & MJG]] and [[Carl Thomas (singer)|Carl Thomas]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Leave Me Alone, Pt. 2\"\n| 2004\n| [[Cam'ron]]\n| ''[[Purple Haze (album)|Purple Haze]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Does Anybody Know\" <small>(produced with [[The Runners]])</small>\n| rowspan=3 | 2005\n| [[Fat Joe]]\n| ''[[All or Nothing (Fat Joe album)|All or Nothing]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Murda Murda\" <small>(produced with [[The Runners]])</small>\n| [[Juelz Santana]] featuring [[Cam'ron]]\n| ''[[What the Game's Been Missing!]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Money on My Mind\" <small>(produced with [[The Runners]])</small>\n| [[Lil Wayne]]\n| ''[[Tha Carter II]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Over Here Hustlin'\"\n| rowspan=6 | 2006\n| [[Birdman (rapper)|Birdman]] & [[Lil Wayne]]\n| rowspan=3 | ''[[Like Father, Like Son (Birdman and Lil Wayne album)|Like Father, Like Son]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Army Gunz\"\n| [[Lil Wayne]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Cali Dro\"\n| [[Birdman (rapper)|Birdman]] & [[Lil Wayne]] featuring [[Tha Dogg Pound]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Gangsta Shit\" <small>(produced with [[Midnight Black]])</small>\n| [[DJ Khaled]] featuring [[Young Jeezy]], [[Bun B]], [[Slick Pulla]] and [[Blood Raw]]\n| ''[[Listennn... the Album]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"[[Grew Up a Screw Up]]\"\n| [[Ludacris]] featuring [[Young Jeezy]]\n| ''[[Release Therapy]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Still On It\" <small>(produced with [[Midnight Black]])</small>\n| [[Young Jeezy]]\n| ''[[The Inspiration]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Relax and Take Notes\"\n| align=center rowspan=3 | 2007\n| [[8Ball & MJG]] featuring [[The Notorious B.I.G.]] and [[Project Pat]]\n| ''[[Ridin High]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"S on My Chest\" <small>(produced with [[Kane Beatz]])</small>\n| [[DJ Khaled]] featuring [[Lil Wayne]] and [[Birdman (rapper)|Birdman]]\n| ''[[We the Best]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"[[I'm Me]]\"\n| [[Lil Wayne]]\n| ''[[The Leak]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Bullet\"\n| align=center rowspan=4 | 2008\n| [[DJ Khaled]] featuring [[Rick Ross]] and [[Cham (singer)|Cham]]\n| ''[[We Global]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"#1 Fan\"\n| [[Plies (rapper)|Plies]] featuring [[Keyshia Cole]] and [[J. Holiday]]\n| ''[[Definition of Real]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"I'm Only Human\"\n| [[Rick Ross]] featuring [[Rodney Jerkins|Rodney]]\n| ''[[Trilla]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Big Time\"\n| [[E-40]] featuring [[Kevin Cossom]]\n| ''[[The Ball Street Journal]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Born an OG\"\n| align=center | 2009\n| [[Ace Hood]] featuring [[Ludacris]]\n| ''[[Ruthless (Ace Hood album)|Ruthless]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"[[All I Do Is Win]]\"\n| align=center rowspan=3 | 2010\n| [[DJ Khaled]] featuring [[T-Pain]], [[Ludacris]], [[Snoop Dogg]] and [[Rick Ross]]\n| ''[[Victory (DJ Khaled album)|Victory]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"All I Do Is Win (Remix)\"\n| [[DJ Khaled]] featuring [[T-Pain]], [[Sean Combs|Diddy]], [[Nicki Minaj]], [[Rick Ross]], [[Busta Rhymes]], [[Fabolous]], [[Jadakiss]], [[Fat Joe]] and [[Swizz Beatz]]\n| {{n/a}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"American Star\"\n| [[Lil Wayne]] featuring [[Shanell]]\n| ''[[Rebirth (Lil Wayne album)|Rebirth]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"[[Welcome to My Hood]]\" <small>(produced with The Renegades and [[DJ Khaled]])</small>\n| rowspan=4 | 2011\n| [[DJ Khaled]] featuring [[Rick Ross]], [[Plies (rapper)|Plies]] and [[Lil Wayne]]\n| rowspan=3 | ''[[We the Best Forever]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Legendary\" <small>(produced with Gary Carolla and [[DJ Khaled]])</small>\n| [[DJ Khaled]] featuring [[Chris Brown (American singer)|Chris Brown]], [[Keyshia Cole]] and [[Ne-Yo]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Welcome to My Hood (Remix)\" <small>(produced with The Renegades and [[DJ Khaled]])</small>\n| [[DJ Khaled]] featuring [[T-Pain]], [[Ludacris]], [[Busta Rhymes]], [[Twista]], [[Mavado (singer)|Mavado]], [[Birdman (rapper)|Birdman]], [[Ace Hood]], [[Game (rapper)|Game]], [[Fat Joe]], [[Jadakiss]], [[Bun B]] and [[Waka Flocka Flame]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Ashes to Ashes\"\n| [[Kevin Cossom]] featuring [[Rick Ross]]\n| ''By Any Means\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Suffering From Success\" <small>(produced with [[Young Chop]] and [[DJ Khaled]])</small>\n| rowspan=2 | 2013\n| [[DJ Khaled]] featuring [[Future (rapper)|Future]] and [[Ace Hood]]\n| rowspan=2 | ''[[Suffering from Success]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"You Don't Want These Problems\" <small>(produced with [[DJ Khaled]], [[Timbaland]] and [[Lee On the Beats]])</small>\n| [[DJ Khaled]] featuring [[Big Sean]], [[Rick Ross]], [[French Montana]], [[2 Chainz]], [[Meek Mill]], [[Ace Hood]] and [[Timbaland]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Wild Thoughts\" <small>(produced with [[Party Next Door]], and [[DJ Khaled]])</small>\n| rowspan=2 | 2017\n| [[DJ Khaled]] featuring [[Rihanna]] and [[Bryson Tiller]]\n| rowspan=2 | ''[[Grateful]]''\n|-\n|}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090106062610/http://www.ozonemag.com/jun2004/text-nastybeatmakers.html Article in ''Ozone'' magazine]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090225234848/http://www.purecashmagazine.com/2008/07/16/nasty-beatmakers/ Interview in ''Pure Cash'' magazine]\n\n{{Cash Money Records}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dj Nasty and Lvm}}\n[[Category:American hip hop record producers]]\n[[Category:American musical duos]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Florida]]\n[[Category:Cash Money Records artists]]\n[[Category:Family musical groups]]\n[[Category:Hip hop duos]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Florida]]\n[[Category:Record production duos]]\n[[Category:Sibling musical duos]]\n[[Category:Southern hip hop musicians]]\n[[Category:African-American record producers]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:SNAP\u2192Snap!,LFO\u2192LFO (American band),Grateful\u2192Grateful (DJ Khaled album)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DJ_Nasty_%26_LVM"}
{"title_page": "11th Bersaglieri Regiment", "text_new": "{{Infobox military unit\n| unit_name =11th Bersaglieri Regiment\n| native_name =11\u00b0 Reggimento Bersaglieri\n| image =CoA mil ITA rgt bersaglieri 11.png\n| alt =160px\n| caption =Regimental coat of arms\n| dates =16 September 1883-1943<br>1992-present\n| country ={{ITA}}\n| countries =\n| allegiance =\n| branch =[[Bersaglieri]]\n| type =Infantry\n| role =\n| size =Regiment\n| command_structure =[[132nd Armored Brigade \"Ariete\"]]\n| garrison = [[Zoppola|Orcenico Superiore]] \n| garrison_label =\n| nickname =\n| patron =\n| motto = \"Quis ultra?\"\n| colours = \n| colours_label = \n| march =\n| mascot =\n| anniversaries =18 June 1836 - Founding of the Bersaglieri\n| equipment =\n| equipment_label =\n| battles =[[First Italo-Ethiopian War]]<br>[[Italo-Turkish War]]<br>[[World War I]]<br>[[World War II]]<br>[[Operation Ancient Babylon]]\n| decorations =[[File:Cavaliere BAR.svg|50px]] [[File:Valor militare gold medal BAR.svg|50px]] [[File:Valor militare silver medal BAR.svg|50px]] [[File:Valor militare silver medal BAR.svg|50px]] [[File:Valor militare silver medal BAR.svg|50px]] [[File:Valor militare silver medal BAR.svg|50px]] [[File:Valor militare bronze medal BAR.svg|50px]] [[File:Valor dell'esercito bronze medal BAR.svg|50px]] [[File:Croce di guerra al valor militare BAR.svg|50px]]<br>1x [[Military Order of Italy]]<br>1x [[Gold Medal of Military Valour]]<br>4x [[Silver Medal of Military Valour|Silver Medals of Military Valour]]<br>1x [[Bronze Medal of Military Valour]]<br>1x Bronze Medal of Army Valour<br>1x [[War Cross of Military Valor]]\n| battle_honours =\n| battle_honours_label =\n| disbanded =\n| flying_hours =\n| website =\n<!-- Commanders -->\n| current_commander =[[Colonel|Col.]] Alessandro Colaiacomo \n| commander1 =\n| commander1_label =\n| commander2 =\n| commander2_label =\n| commander3 =\n| commander3_label =\n| commander4 =\n| commander4_label =\n| commander5 =\n| commander5_label =\n| commander6 =\n| commander6_label =\n| commander7 =\n| commander7_label =\n| commander8 =\n| commander8_label =\n| commander9 =\n| commander9_label =\n| notable_commanders =\n<!-- Insignia -->\n| identification_symbol = {{Inline block|[[File:Mostrina - Bersaglieri.png|32px]]|div}} {{Inline block|style=transform: scaleX(-1);|[[File:Mostrina - Bersaglieri.png|32px]]|div}}\n| identification_symbol_label = Bersaglieri [[Italian Army gorget patches|gorget patches]]\n| identification_symbol_2 =\n| identification_symbol_2_label =\n| identification_symbol_3 =\n| identification_symbol_3_label =\n| identification_symbol_4 =\n| identification_symbol_4_label =\n| identification_symbol_5 =\n| identification_symbol_5_label =\n}}\n\nThe '''11th Bersaglieri Regiment''' ({{lang-it|11\u00b0 Reggimento Bersaglieri}}) is an active unit of the [[Italian Army]] based in [[Zoppola|Orcenico Superiore]] in the [[Friuli-Venezia Giulia]] region. The regiment is part of the army's infantry corps' [[Bersaglieri]] speciality and operationally assigned to the [[132nd Armored Brigade \"Ariete\"]].<ref>{{cite web |title=11\u00b0 Reggimento Bersaglieri |url=http://www.esercito.difesa.it/organizzazione/capo-di-sme/Comando-Forze-Operative-Nord/Divisione-Vittorio-Veneto/Brigata-Corazzata-Ariete/11-Reggimento-Bersaglieri |publisher=Italian Army |accessdate=5 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe 11th Bersaglieri Regiment was established on 16 September 1883 in [[Caserta]].<ref name=\"11BersSto\">{{cite web|title=La Storia|url=http://www.esercito.difesa.it/organizzazione/capo-di-sme/Comando-Forze-Operative-Nord/Divisione-Friuli/Brigata-Corazzata-Ariete/11-Reggimento-Bersaglieri/Pagine/La-Storia.aspx|website=www.esercito.difesa.it|accessdate=10 October 2017|language=it|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171011072350/http://www.esercito.difesa.it/organizzazione/capo-di-sme/Comando-Forze-Operative-Nord/Divisione-Friuli/Brigata-Corazzata-Ariete/11-Reggimento-Bersaglieri/Pagine/La-Storia.aspx|archive-date=2017-10-11|url-status=live}}</ref> The newly established unit was composed of the fourth battalions of the 1st, 4th and 7th Bersaglieri regiments. Initially the battalions of the 11th Bersaglieri Regiment were named I, II, and III Battalions,<ref name=\"11RgtANB\">{{cite web|title=11\u00b0 Reggimento \u2013 ASSOCIAZIONE NAZIONALE BERSAGLIERI|url=https://www.bersaglieri.net/11-reggimento/|website=www.bersaglieri.net|accessdate=10 October 2017|language=it-IT|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171011072206/https://www.bersaglieri.net/11-reggimento/|archive-date=2017-10-11|url-status=live}}</ref> but in 1886 the battalions were assigned their traditional numbers: XV, XXVII, and XXXIII. The XI Cyclists Battalion was added in 1910, while the XXXIX Battalion was raised in 1915 to replace the XV Battalion, which had been deployed to [[Italian Libya]] that year.<ref name=\"11RgtANB\" />\n\nThe 11th Bersaglieri Regiment was involved in the [[First Italo-Ethiopian War]] in 1895 and in the [[Italo-Turkish War]] in 1911.<ref name=\"11RgtBersRegioEsercito\">{{cite web|title=11\u00b0 Reggimento Bersaglieri|url=http://www.regioesercito.it/reparti/bersaglieri/rgtbers11.htm|website=Regio Esercito|accessdate=10 October 2017|language=Italian|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305073528/http://www.regioesercito.it/reparti/bersaglieri/rgtbers11.htm|archive-date=2016-03-05|url-status=live}}</ref> During the latter war the regiment's XXVII Battalion conquered Sciara Sciat, near [[Tripoli]]. For this action the 11th Bersaglieri Regiment was awarded a [[Gold Medal of Military Valour]].<ref name=\"RadunoBersaglieri17\">{{cite web|title=Storia dei Bersaglieri - Raduno Nazionale Bersaglieri 2017 - Pescara|url=http://radunobersaglieri2017.it/i-bersaglieri/storia-dei-bersaglieri/|website=Raduno Nazionale Bersaglieri 2017 - Pescara|accessdate=11 October 2017|language=it-IT|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171011130653/http://radunobersaglieri2017.it/i-bersaglieri/storia-dei-bersaglieri/|archive-date=2017-10-11|url-status=dead}}</ref> However the massacre of captured Italian prisoners by Osman forces<ref name=\"Gooch2014\">{{cite book|author=John Gooch|title=The Italian Army and the First World War|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pCOjAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA44|date=19 June 2014|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-19307-8|pages=44\u2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Duggan2008\">{{cite book|author=Christopher Duggan|title=The Force of Destiny: A History of Italy Since 1796|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lSRwOZ0Yxw8C&pg=PA382|year=2008|publisher=Houghton Mifflin Harcourt|isbn=0-618-35367-4|pages=382\u2013}}</ref> led to a [[1911 Tripoli massacre|massive reprisal]]. The 11th Bersaglieri Regiment also fought in [[Assaba]], for which it was awarded a [[Bronze Medal of Military Valour]].<ref name=\"RadunoBersaglieri17\" />\n\n=== World War I ===\n{{See also|Bersaglieri#World War I}}\nDuring [[World War I]], the 11th Regiment, then headquartered in [[Ancona]], was initially assigned to various Infantry Divisions until 11 February 1916 when it entered the II Bersaglieri Brigade - first together with the [[9th Bersaglieri Regiment]] and later with the [[7th Bersaglieri Regiment]].<ref name=\"11BersSto\" /> The 11th Bersaglieri Regiment served in Log di Cezsoca, [[Srpenica]], Chiont, and Dogna Valley.<ref name=\"IIBrigBersFdP\">{{cite web|title=II Brigata Bersaglieri|url=http://www.frontedelpiave.info/public/modules/Fronte_del_Piave_article/Fronte_del_Piave_view_article.php?id_a=552&app_l2=527&app_l3=552&sito=Fronte-del-Piave&titolo=II-Brigata|website=FronteDelPiave.info|accessdate=10 October 2017|language=Italian|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171011072651/http://www.frontedelpiave.info/public/modules/Fronte_del_Piave_article/Fronte_del_Piave_view_article.php?id_a=552&app_l2=527&app_l3=552&sito=Fronte-del-Piave&titolo=II-Brigata|archive-date=2017-10-11|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 June 1917, the II Bersaglieri Brigade was take out of the frontline for rest, but only two days later it had to return as on 3 June 1917 the Royal Italian Army began its [[Tenth Battle of the Isonzo|Tenth offensive along the Isonzo river]]. The 11th Bersaglieri Regiment was finally taken out of the front on 7 November 1917.<ref name=\"IIBrigBersFdP\" /> On 3 November 1918 the 11th Bersaglieri Regiment entered Trieste.<ref name=\"IlPiccolo3Nov08\">{{cite news|title=Cittadinanza onoraria oggi ai bersaglieri - Il Piccolo|url=http://ricerca.gelocal.it/ilpiccolo/archivio/ilpiccolo/2008/11/03/NZ_14_SPAL.html|accessdate=10 October 2017|work=Archivio - Il Piccolo|date=3 November 2008|language=it|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171011073322/http://ricerca.gelocal.it/ilpiccolo/archivio/ilpiccolo/2008/11/03/NZ_14_SPAL.html|archive-date=2017-10-11|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nDuring the war the 11th regiment's depot raised the LI Autonomous Battalion, the LXVI Battalion for the 17th Bersaglieri Regiment, and the LXVII Battalion for the [[18th Bersaglieri Regiment]]. The 11th regiment consisted of the XXVII, XXXIII, XXXIX battalions, while the XI Cyclists Battalion fought as autonomous unit.<ref name=\"IIBrigBersFdP\" /> After the XV Battalion departed Libya on 28 May 1918 it was assigned on 29 June 1918 to the 5th Group of 2nd Assault Division.<ref name=\"11RgtBersFdP\">{{cite web|title=11\u00b0 Reggimento Bersaglieri|url=http://www.frontedelpiave.info/public/modules/Fronte_del_Piave_article/Fronte_del_Piave_view_article.php?id_a=538&app_l2=527&app_l3=538&sito=Fronte-del-Piave&titolo=11%C2%B0-Reggimento|website=FronteDelPiave.info|accessdate=10 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170502175352/http://www.frontedelpiave.info/public/modules/Fronte_del_Piave_article/Fronte_del_Piave_view_article.php?id_a=538&app_l2=527&app_l3=538&sito=Fronte-del-Piave&titolo=11%C2%B0-Reggimento|archive-date=2017-05-02|url-status=live}}</ref> For its conduct at [[Doberd\u00f2 del Lago|Jamiano]] the regiment was awarded a [[Silver Medal of Military Valour]], while the XI Cyclists Battalion was awarded three Silver Medals of Military Valour: one for the conquest of [[Monte San Michele]] in 1916, one for the tenacious defense of Hill 144 east of [[Monfalcone]] between 14\u201316 September 1916, and one for the breakthrough of enemy lines at [[Revine Lago]] on 30 October 1918.\n\nDuring World War I, the 11th Bersaglieri Regiment was headquartered in Ancona, and recruited from [[Benevento]], [[Cosenza]], [[Ferrara]], [[Gaeta]], [[Lecce]], [[Massa]], [[Milan]], and [[Savona]] Districts, while mobilized troops also from [[Ascoli Piceno]], [[Chieti]], [[Macerata]], [[Sulmona]], [[Teramo]], and [[Campobasso]] Districts.<ref name=\"11RgtBersFdP\" />\n\nAlongside military operations, the 11th Bersaglieri Regiment provided [[disaster relief]] in the [[1915 Avezzano earthquake]].<ref name=\"RadunoBersaglieri17\" />\n\n=== Inter-war ===\nIn 1919 the XI Cyclists Battalion was disbanded and in 1920 the regiment's strength was reduced to two battalions and one reserve battalion.<ref name=\"11RgtANB\" /> Some Bersaglieri of the 11th regiment were involved in the unsanctioned [[Italian Regency of Carnaro#Impresa di Fiume|\"Fiume Exploit\"]].<ref name=\"RadunoBersaglieri17\" />\n\nOn 7 July 1924 the regiment was transformed in a cyclists regiment and the reserve battalion was disbanded; on 11 March 1926 the 11th Regiment was reorganized and now consisted of a regimental command, a depot, the XV Battalion, and the XXVII Battalion.<ref name=\"11RgtBersRegioEsercito\" /> During the [[Second Italo-Ethiopian War]], the 11th Bersaglieri Regiment provided officers and troops to several mobilized units.<ref name=\"11RgtBersRegioEsercito\" />\n\n=== World War II ===\nOn 1 February 1938, the 11th Bersaglieri Regiment, together with the cavalry regiments [[Regiment \"Piemonte Cavalleria\" (2nd)|\"Piemonte Reale\" (2nd)]] and [[Regiment \"Cavalleggeri di Saluzzo\" (12th)|\"Cavalleggeri di Saluzzo\" (12th)]], the 1st Fast Artillery Regiment, and the 1st Light Tank Group \"San Giusto\", were assigned to the [[1st Cavalry Division Eugenio di Savoia|1st Fast Division \"Eugenio di Savoia\"]].<ref name=\"11BersSto\" /><ref name=\"11RgtBersRegioEsercito\" />\n\nOn 6 March 1941, the 11th Bersaglieri Regiment was deployed to the [[Vipava Valley]] and on 11 April the whole Division participated in the [[Axis invasion of Yugoslavia]].<ref name=\"11RgtBersRegioEsercito\" /> In a few days 1st Fast Division occupied the whole of [[Dalmatia]].<ref name=\"11RgtBersRegioEsercito\" /> Between late 1941 and late 1942 the 11th Bersaglieri Regiment carried out intense [[counter-insurgency]] activity against [[Yugoslav Partisans]].<ref name=\"11RgtBersRegioEsercito\" /> In October 1942 the regiment returned from [[\u0160ibenik]] to [[Vodice, Croatia|Vodice]] in Dalmatia. There it fought in June 1943 in the attempt to clear [[Zuta Lovka]] from partisans.<ref name=\"11RgtBersRegioEsercito\" /> The 11th Bersaglieri Regiment was disbaned on 9 September 1943 in Dalmatia after Italy had switched sides with the [[Armistice of Cassibile]].<ref name=\"11BersSto\" /><ref name=\"11RgtBersRegioEsercito\" />\n\nDuring World War II, the 11th Bersaglieri Regiment included the Regimental command, the Command Company, XV Bersaglieri Cyclists Battalion, XXVII Bersaglieri Cyclists Battalion, XXXIII Bersaglieri Cyclists Battalion, LI Replacements Battalion, 271st Armoured Car Company, and 11th Anti-tank Company.<ref name=\"11RgtBersRegioEsercito\" />\n\n=== Cold War ===\nIn 1964 the XI Bersaglieri Battalion was reformed in [[Sacile]] as part of the [[182nd Armored Infantry Regiment \"Garibaldi\"]].<ref name=\"11RgtANB\" /> It remained the only active battalion of the 11th Bersaglieri Regiment until the [[Italian Army 1975 reform|1975 Italian Army reform]].\n\n==== 27th Bersaglieri Battalion \"Jamiano\" ====\nDuring the same reform the [[132nd Tank Regiment (Italy)|132nd Tank Regiment]] was disbanded on 31 October 1975 and the regiment's XXXVIII Bersaglieri Battalion was renamed 27th Bersaglieri Battalion \"Jamiano\" the next day. The 27th Bersaglieri Battalion \"Jamiano\" inherited the war flag and traditions of the 11th Bersaglieri Regiment.<ref name=\"11BersSto\" /> The battalion was assigned to the [[132nd Armored Brigade \"Manin\"]].<ref name=\"11BersSto\" /><ref name=\"11RgtANB\" /> Bersaglieri battalions created during the reform were named, with two exceptions, for battles in which Bersaglieri units had distinguished themselves: the 27th Bersaglieri Battalion was named for its defense of Hill 144 in [[Jamiano]] in 1917.\n\n=== 1992-onwards ===\n[[File:Italian Army - 11th Bersaglieri Regiment war flag at the 66th National Rally of the Bersaglieri 2018.png|thumb|right|11th Bersaglieri Regiment war flag at the 66th National Rally of the Bersaglieri]]\nOn 30 September 1992 the 27th Bersaglieri Battalion \"Jamiano\" entered the re-established 11th Bersaglieri Regiment in [[Aviano]].<ref name=\"11RgtANB\" /> On 21 November 1992 the 11th Bersaglieri Regiment moved to Orcenico Superiore, where on 18 April 1997, the 27th Bersaglieri Battalion was renamed [[11th Bersaglieri Battalion \"Caprera\"]],<ref name=\"11BersSto\" /> reunting all traditions and awards bestowed to the 11th Bersaglieri Regiment and its battalions in one unit, and gaining the tradition of the [[182nd Armored Infantry Regiment \"Garibaldi\"]] to wear the red tie with the formal uniform.<ref name=\"11RgtANB\" />\n\nIn the night of 6 April 2004, during the 11th Bersaglieri Regiment's service in Iraq as part of [[Operation Ancient Babylon]], the forces of [[Muqtada al-Sadr]]'s [[Peace Companies|Mahdi Army]] occupied the three main bridges in [[Nasiriyah]]. Three companies of the 11th Regiment, one squadron of the [[Regiment \"Savoia Cavalleria\" (3rd)]], and some logistical units of the [[132nd Armored Brigade \"Ariete\"]] engaged in an 18-hours long firefight with the rebel forces.<ref name=\"MessaggeroVeneto15May04\">{{cite news|title=Insurrezione a Nassiriya, fuoco sugli italiani - Messaggero Veneto|url=http://ricerca.gelocal.it/messaggeroveneto/archivio/messaggeroveneto/2004/05/15/NZ_03_SEB2.html?ref=search|accessdate=11 October 2017|work=Archivio - Messaggero Veneto|date=15 May 2004|language=it|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171012044116/http://ricerca.gelocal.it/messaggeroveneto/archivio/messaggeroveneto/2004/05/15/NZ_03_SEB2.html?ref=search|archive-date=2017-10-12|url-status=live}}</ref> For retaking the three bridges the 11th Bersaglieri Regiment was decorated with a [[War Cross for Military Valor]] in 2008.\n\n== Commanders ==\n* Colonel Giuseppe Barbiani (24 May - 1 December 1915);\n* Colonel Giovanni Beruto, (3 December 1915 - 13 January 1917);\n* Lieutenant Colonel Giovanni Capoani (19 January 1917 - 15 February 1917);\n* Colonel Gino Graziani (10 March 1917 - end of hostilities);\n* Colonel Vincenzo Robertiello;\n* Colonel Guglielmo Mingo;\n* Colonel Michele Adabbo;\n* Colonel Lalli (1943);\n* Colonel Alessandro Guarisco;<ref name=\"MessaggeroVeneto11Feb06\">{{cite news|title=Cambio di comando all'11\u00ba reggimento bersaglieri - Messaggero Veneto|url=http://ricerca.gelocal.it/messaggeroveneto/archivio/messaggeroveneto/2006/02/11/PN_15_DTD7.html|accessdate=11 October 2017|work=Archivio - Messaggero Veneto|date=11 February 2006|language=it|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171011130308/http://ricerca.gelocal.it/messaggeroveneto/archivio/messaggeroveneto/2006/02/11/PN_15_DTD7.html|archive-date=2017-10-11|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Colonel Michele Cittadella;<ref name=\"MessaggeroVeneto11Feb06\" />\n* Colonel Fabio Polli;\n* Colonel Salvatore Daniele Patan\u00e8 (2010-2011);\n* Colonel Alfonso Cornacchia (2011-2013);<ref name=\"MessaggeroVeneto5Oct13\">{{cite news|title=Cornacchia passa a Dess\u00ec il comando della Leccis|url=http://messaggeroveneto.gelocal.it/udine/cronaca/2013/10/05/news/cornacchia-passa-a-dessi-il-comando-della-leccis-foto-1.7867648|accessdate=11 October 2017|work=Messaggero Veneto|date=5 October 2013|language=it|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171011072621/http://messaggeroveneto.gelocal.it/udine/cronaca/2013/10/05/news/cornacchia-passa-a-dessi-il-comando-della-leccis-foto-1.7867648|archive-date=2017-10-11|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Colonel Eugenio Dess\u00ec (2013-2015);<ref name=\"Gazzettino25Jul15\">{{cite news|title=Brigata Ariete, cambio al vertice  del reggimento dei bersaglieri|url=http://www.ilgazzettino.it/pay/pordenone_pay/brigata_ariete_cambio_al_vertice_reggimento_bersaglieri-1160763.html|accessdate=11 October 2017|work=Il Gazzettino|date=25 July 2015|language=Italian|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171011073337/http://www.ilgazzettino.it/pay/pordenone_pay/brigata_ariete_cambio_al_vertice_reggimento_bersaglieri-1160763.html|archive-date=2017-10-11|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Colonel Alessandro Colaiacomo (2015\u2013present).<ref name=\"Gazzettino25Jul15\" />\n\n== Current Structure ==\nAs of 2019 the 11th Bersaglieri Regiment consists of:\n\n* [[File:CoA mil ITA rgt bersaglieri 11.png|30px]] '''Regimental Command''', in [[Zoppola|Orcenico Superiore]]\n** Command and Logistic Support Company \"Sciara Sciat\"\n** '''11th Bersaglieri Battalion \"[[Caprera]]\"'''\n*** 1st Fusiliers Company \"Jamiano\"\n*** 2nd Fusiliers Company \"San Michele\"\n*** 3rd Fusiliers Company \"Nasiriyya\"\n*** Maneuver Support Company \"Assaba\"\n\nThe Command and Logistic Support Company fields the following platoons: [[Command and control|C3 Platoon]], [[Materiel|Transport and Materiel Platoon]], [[Military medicine|Medical Platoon]], and [[Military commissariat|Commissariat Platoon]]. The regiment is equipped with tracked [[Dardo IFV|Dardo]] [[infantry fighting vehicles]]. The Maneuver Support Company is equipped with [[M106 mortar carrier|M106 120mm mortar carriers]] and Dardo IFVs with [[Spike (missile)|Spike LR]] [[anti-tank guided missiles]].\n\n== Uniform ==\nIn order to display the lineage of the 182nd Armored Infantry Regiment \"Garibaldi\", soldiers of the 11th Bersaglieri Battalion \"Caprera\" wear the red tie.<ref name=\"11BersSto\" />\n\n== Notable members ==\nFrom 13 September 1915 to 28 December 1918, [[Benito Mussolini]] served in the 11th Regiment.<ref name=\"ArchivioMussolini\">{{cite web|last1=Scarpellini|first1=Fulco|title=Copia del Foglio Matricolare di Benito Mussolini|url=http://www.larchivio.com/xoom/matricolare.htm|website=www.larchivio.com|accessdate=10 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170927034627/http://www.larchivio.com/xoom/matricolare.htm|archive-date=2017-09-27|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Bersaglieri]]\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.esercito.difesa.it/organizzazione/capo-di-sme/Comando-Forze-Operative-Nord/Divisione-Vittorio-Veneto/Brigata-Corazzata-Ariete/11-Reggimento-Bersaglieri Italian Army Website: 11th Bersaglieri Regiment]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|1}}\n\n{{Italian Army}}\n{{Italian Army Bersaglieri Regiments}}\n\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 1883]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations disestablished in 1943]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 1992]]\n[[Category:Regiments of Italy in World War I]]\n[[Category:Regiments of Italy in World War II]]\n[[Category:Bersaglieri Regiments of Italy]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military unit\n| unit_name =11th Bersaglieri Regiment\n| native_name =11\u00b0 Reggimento Bersaglieri\n| image =CoA mil ITA rgt bersaglieri 11.png\n| alt =160px\n| caption =Regimental coat of arms\n| dates =16 September 1883-1943<br>1992-present\n| country ={{ITA}}\n| countries =\n| allegiance =\n| branch =[[Bersaglieri]]\n| type =Infantry\n| role =\n| size =Regiment\n| command_structure =[[132nd Armored Brigade \"Ariete\"]]\n| garrison = [[Zoppola|Orcenico Superiore]] \n| garrison_label =\n| nickname =\n| patron =\n| motto = \"Quis ultra?\"\n| colours = \n| colours_label = \n| march =\n| mascot =\n| anniversaries =18 June 1836 - Founding of the Bersaglieri\n| equipment =\n| equipment_label =\n| battles =[[First Italo-Ethiopian War]]<br>[[Italo-Turkish War]]<br>[[World War I]]<br>[[World War II]]<br>[[Operation Ancient Babylon]]\n| decorations =[[File:Cavaliere BAR.svg|50px]] [[File:Valor militare gold medal BAR.svg|50px]] [[File:Valor militare silver medal BAR.svg|50px]] [[File:Valor militare silver medal BAR.svg|50px]] [[File:Valor militare silver medal BAR.svg|50px]] [[File:Valor militare silver medal BAR.svg|50px]] [[File:Valor militare bronze medal BAR.svg|50px]] [[File:Valor dell'esercito bronze medal BAR.svg|50px]] [[File:Croce di guerra al valor militare BAR.svg|50px]]<br>1x [[Military Order of Italy]]<br>1x [[Gold Medal of Military Valour]]<br>4x [[Silver Medal of Military Valour|Silver Medals of Military Valour]]<br>1x [[Bronze Medal of Military Valour]]<br>1x Bronze Medal of Army Valour<br>1x [[War Cross of Military Valor]]\n| battle_honours =\n| battle_honours_label =\n| disbanded =\n| flying_hours =\n| website =\n<!-- Commanders -->\n| current_commander =[[Colonel|Col.]] Alessandro Colaiacomo \n| commander1 =\n| commander1_label =\n| commander2 =\n| commander2_label =\n| commander3 =\n| commander3_label =\n| commander4 =\n| commander4_label =\n| commander5 =\n| commander5_label =\n| commander6 =\n| commander6_label =\n| commander7 =\n| commander7_label =\n| commander8 =\n| commander8_label =\n| commander9 =\n| commander9_label =\n| notable_commanders =\n<!-- Insignia -->\n| identification_symbol = {{Inline block|[[File:Mostrina - Bersaglieri.png|32px]]|div}} {{Inline block|style=transform: scaleX(-1);|[[File:Mostrina - Bersaglieri.png|32px]]|div}}\n| identification_symbol_label = Bersaglieri [[Italian Army gorget patches|gorget patches]]\n| identification_symbol_2 =\n| identification_symbol_2_label =\n| identification_symbol_3 =\n| identification_symbol_3_label =\n| identification_symbol_4 =\n| identification_symbol_4_label =\n| identification_symbol_5 =\n| identification_symbol_5_label =\n}}\n\nThe '''11th Bersaglieri Regiment''' ({{lang-it|11\u00b0 Reggimento Bersaglieri}}) is an active unit of the [[Italian Army]] based in [[Zoppola|Orcenico Superiore]] in the [[Friuli-Venezia Giulia]] region. The regiment is part of the army's infantry corps' [[Bersaglieri]] speciality and operationally assigned to the [[132nd Armored Brigade \"Ariete\"]].<ref>{{cite web |title=11\u00b0 Reggimento Bersaglieri |url=http://www.esercito.difesa.it/organizzazione/capo-di-sme/Comando-Forze-Operative-Nord/Divisione-Vittorio-Veneto/Brigata-Corazzata-Ariete/11-Reggimento-Bersaglieri |publisher=Italian Army |accessdate=5 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe 11th Bersaglieri Regiment was established on 16 September 1883 in [[Caserta]].<ref name=\"11BersSto\">{{cite web|title=La Storia|url=http://www.esercito.difesa.it/organizzazione/capo-di-sme/Comando-Forze-Operative-Nord/Divisione-Friuli/Brigata-Corazzata-Ariete/11-Reggimento-Bersaglieri/Pagine/La-Storia.aspx|website=www.esercito.difesa.it|accessdate=10 October 2017|language=it|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171011072350/http://www.esercito.difesa.it/organizzazione/capo-di-sme/Comando-Forze-Operative-Nord/Divisione-Friuli/Brigata-Corazzata-Ariete/11-Reggimento-Bersaglieri/Pagine/La-Storia.aspx|archive-date=2017-10-11|url-status=live}}</ref> The newly established unit was composed of the fourth battalions of the 1st, 4th and 7th Bersaglieri regiments. Initially the battalions of the 11th Bersaglieri Regiment were named I, II, and III Battalions,<ref name=\"11RgtANB\">{{cite web|title=11\u00b0 Reggimento \u2013 ASSOCIAZIONE NAZIONALE BERSAGLIERI|url=https://www.bersaglieri.net/11-reggimento/|website=www.bersaglieri.net|accessdate=10 October 2017|language=it-IT|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171011072206/https://www.bersaglieri.net/11-reggimento/|archive-date=2017-10-11|url-status=live}}</ref> but in 1886 the battalions were assigned their traditional numbers: XV, XXVII, and XXXIII. The XI Cyclists Battalion was added in 1910, while the XXXIX Battalion was raised in 1915 to replace the XV Battalion, which had been deployed to [[Italian Libya]] that year.<ref name=\"11RgtANB\" />\n\nThe 11th Bersaglieri Regiment was involved in the [[First Italo-Ethiopian War]] in 1895 and in the [[Italo-Turkish War]] in 1911.<ref name=\"11RgtBersRegioEsercito\">{{cite web|title=11\u00b0 Reggimento Bersaglieri|url=http://www.regioesercito.it/reparti/bersaglieri/rgtbers11.htm|website=Regio Esercito|accessdate=10 October 2017|language=Italian|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305073528/http://www.regioesercito.it/reparti/bersaglieri/rgtbers11.htm|archive-date=2016-03-05|url-status=live}}</ref> During the latter war the regiment's XXVII Battalion conquered Sciara Sciat, near [[Tripoli]]. For this action the 11th Bersaglieri Regiment was awarded a [[Gold Medal of Military Valour]].<ref name=\"RadunoBersaglieri17\">{{cite web|title=Storia dei Bersaglieri - Raduno Nazionale Bersaglieri 2017 - Pescara|url=http://radunobersaglieri2017.it/i-bersaglieri/storia-dei-bersaglieri/|website=Raduno Nazionale Bersaglieri 2017 - Pescara|accessdate=11 October 2017|language=it-IT|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171011130653/http://radunobersaglieri2017.it/i-bersaglieri/storia-dei-bersaglieri/|archive-date=2017-10-11|url-status=dead}}</ref> However the massacre of captured Italian prisoners by Osman forces<ref name=\"Gooch2014\">{{cite book|author=John Gooch|title=The Italian Army and the First World War|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pCOjAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA44|date=19 June 2014|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-19307-8|pages=44\u2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Duggan2008\">{{cite book|author=Christopher Duggan|title=The Force of Destiny: A History of Italy Since 1796|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lSRwOZ0Yxw8C&pg=PA382|year=2008|publisher=Houghton Mifflin Harcourt|isbn=0-618-35367-4|pages=382\u2013}}</ref> led to a [[1911 Tripoli massacre|massive reprisal]]. The 11th Bersaglieri Regiment also fought in [[Assaba]], for which it was awarded a [[Bronze Medal of Military Valour]].<ref name=\"RadunoBersaglieri17\" />\n\n=== World War I ===\n{{See also|Bersaglieri#World War I}}\nDuring [[World War I]], the 11th Regiment, then headquartered in [[Ancona]], was initially assigned to various Infantry Divisions until 11 February 1916 when it entered the II Bersaglieri Brigade - first together with the [[9th Bersaglieri Regiment]] and later with the [[7th Bersaglieri Regiment]].<ref name=\"11BersSto\" /> The 11th Bersaglieri Regiment served in Log di Cezsoca, [[Srpenica]], Chiont, and Dogna Valley.<ref name=\"IIBrigBersFdP\">{{cite web|title=II Brigata Bersaglieri|url=http://www.frontedelpiave.info/public/modules/Fronte_del_Piave_article/Fronte_del_Piave_view_article.php?id_a=552&app_l2=527&app_l3=552&sito=Fronte-del-Piave&titolo=II-Brigata|website=FronteDelPiave.info|accessdate=10 October 2017|language=Italian|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171011072651/http://www.frontedelpiave.info/public/modules/Fronte_del_Piave_article/Fronte_del_Piave_view_article.php?id_a=552&app_l2=527&app_l3=552&sito=Fronte-del-Piave&titolo=II-Brigata|archive-date=2017-10-11|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 June 1917, the II Bersaglieri Brigade was take out of the frontline for rest, but only two days later it had to return as on 3 June 1917 the Royal Italian Army began its [[Tenth Battle of the Isonzo|Tenth offensive along the Isonzo river]]. The 11th Bersaglieri Regiment was finally taken out of the front on 7 November 1917.<ref name=\"IIBrigBersFdP\" /> On 3 November 1918 the 11th Bersaglieri Regiment entered Trieste.<ref name=\"IlPiccolo3Nov08\">{{cite news|title=Cittadinanza onoraria oggi ai bersaglieri - Il Piccolo|url=http://ricerca.gelocal.it/ilpiccolo/archivio/ilpiccolo/2008/11/03/NZ_14_SPAL.html|accessdate=10 October 2017|work=Archivio - Il Piccolo|date=3 November 2008|language=it|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171011073322/http://ricerca.gelocal.it/ilpiccolo/archivio/ilpiccolo/2008/11/03/NZ_14_SPAL.html|archive-date=2017-10-11|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nDuring the war the 11th regiment's depot raised the LI Autonomous Battalion, the LXVI Battalion for the 17th Bersaglieri Regiment, and the LXVII Battalion for the [[18th Bersaglieri Regiment]]. The 11th regiment consisted of the XXVII, XXXIII, XXXIX battalions, while the XI Cyclists Battalion fought as autonomous unit.<ref name=\"IIBrigBersFdP\" /> After the XV Battalion departed Libya on 28 May 1918 it was assigned on 29 June 1918 to the 5th Group of 2nd Assault Division.<ref name=\"11RgtBersFdP\">{{cite web|title=11\u00b0 Reggimento Bersaglieri|url=http://www.frontedelpiave.info/public/modules/Fronte_del_Piave_article/Fronte_del_Piave_view_article.php?id_a=538&app_l2=527&app_l3=538&sito=Fronte-del-Piave&titolo=11%C2%B0-Reggimento|website=FronteDelPiave.info|accessdate=10 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170502175352/http://www.frontedelpiave.info/public/modules/Fronte_del_Piave_article/Fronte_del_Piave_view_article.php?id_a=538&app_l2=527&app_l3=538&sito=Fronte-del-Piave&titolo=11%C2%B0-Reggimento|archive-date=2017-05-02|url-status=live}}</ref> For its conduct at [[Doberd\u00f2 del Lago|Jamiano]] the regiment was awarded a [[Silver Medal of Military Valour]], while the XI Cyclists Battalion was awarded three Silver Medals of Military Valour: one for the conquest of [[Monte San Michele]] in 1916, one for the tenacious defense of Hill 144 east of [[Monfalcone]] between 14-16 September 1916, and one for the breakthrough of enemy lines at [[Revine Lago]] on 30 October 1918.\n\nDuring World War I, the 11th Bersaglieri Regiment was headquartered in Ancona, and recruited from [[Benevento]], [[Cosenza]], [[Ferrara]], [[Gaeta]], [[Lecce]], [[Massa]], [[Milan]], and [[Savona]] Districts, while mobilized troops also from [[Ascoli Piceno]], [[Chieti]], [[Macerata]], [[Sulmona]], [[Teramo]], and [[Campobasso]] Districts.<ref name=\"11RgtBersFdP\" />\n\nAlongside military operations, the 11th Bersaglieri Regiment provided [[disaster relief]] in the [[1915 Avezzano earthquake]].<ref name=\"RadunoBersaglieri17\" />\n\n=== Inter-war ===\nIn 1919 the XI Cyclists Battalion was disbanded and in 1920 the regiment's strength was reduced to two battalions and one reserve battalion.<ref name=\"11RgtANB\" /> Some Bersaglieri of the 11th regiment were involved in the unsanctioned [[Italian Regency of Carnaro#Impresa di Fiume|\"Fiume Exploit\"]].<ref name=\"RadunoBersaglieri17\" />\n\nOn 7 July 1924 the regiment was transformed in a cyclists regiment and the reserve battalion was disbanded; on 11 March 1926 the 11th Regiment was reorganized and now consisted of a regimental command, a depot, the XV Battalion, and the XXVII Battalion.<ref name=\"11RgtBersRegioEsercito\" /> During the [[Second Italo-Ethiopian War]], the 11th Bersaglieri Regiment provided officers and troops to several mobilized units.<ref name=\"11RgtBersRegioEsercito\" />\n\n=== World War II ===\nOn 1 February 1938, the 11th Bersaglieri Regiment, together with the cavalry regiments [[Regiment \"Piemonte Cavalleria\" (2nd)|\"Piemonte Reale\" (2nd)]] and [[Regiment \"Cavalleggeri di Saluzzo\" (12th)|\"Cavalleggeri di Saluzzo\" (12th)]], the 1st Fast Artillery Regiment, and the 1st Light Tank Group \"San Giusto\", were assigned to the [[1st Cavalry Division Eugenio di Savoia|1st Fast Division \"Eugenio di Savoia\"]].<ref name=\"11BersSto\" /><ref name=\"11RgtBersRegioEsercito\" />\n\nOn 6 March 1941, the 11th Bersaglieri Regiment was deployed to the [[Vipava Valley]] and on 11 April the whole Division particiapted in the [[Axis invasion of Yugoslavia]].<ref name=\"11RgtBersRegioEsercito\" /> In a few days 1st Fast Division occupied the whole of [[Dalmatia]].<ref name=\"11RgtBersRegioEsercito\" /> Between late 1941 and late 1942 the 11th Bersaglieri Regiment carried out intense [[counter-insurgency]] activity against [[Yugoslav Partisans]].<ref name=\"11RgtBersRegioEsercito\" /> In October 1942 the regiment returned from [[\u0160ibenik]] to [[Vodice, Croatia|Vodice]] in Dalmatia. There it fought in June 1943 in the attempt to clear [[Zuta Lovka]] from partisans.<ref name=\"11RgtBersRegioEsercito\" /> The 11th Bersaglieri Regiment was disbaned on 9 September 1943 in Dalmatia after Italy had switched sides with the [[Armistice of Cassibile]].<ref name=\"11BersSto\" /><ref name=\"11RgtBersRegioEsercito\" />\n\nDuring World War II, the 11th Bersaglieri Regiment included the Regimental command, the Command Company, XV Bersaglieri Cyclists Battalion, XXVII Bersaglieri Cyclists Battalion, XXXIII Bersaglieri Cyclists Battalion, LI Replacements Battalion, 271st Armoured Car Company, and 11th Anti-tank Company.<ref name=\"11RgtBersRegioEsercito\" />\n\n=== Cold War ===\nIn 1964 the XI Bersaglieri Battalion was reformed in [[Sacile]] as part of the [[182nd Armored Infantry Regiment \"Garibaldi\"]].<ref name=\"11RgtANB\" /> It remained the only active battalion of the 11th Bersaglieri Regiment until the [[Italian Army 1975 reform|1975 Italian Army reform]].\n\n==== 27th Bersaglieri Battalion \"Jamiano\" ====\nDuring the same reform the [[132nd Tank Regiment (Italy)|132nd Tank Regiment]] was disbanded on 31 October 1975 and the regiment's XXXVIII Bersaglieri Battalion was renamed 27th Bersaglieri Battalion \"Jamiano\" the next day. The 27th Bersaglieri Battalion \"Jamiano\" inherited the war flag and traditions of the 11th Bersaglieri Regiment.<ref name=\"11BersSto\" /> The battalion was assigned to the [[132nd Armored Brigade \"Manin\"]].<ref name=\"11BersSto\" /><ref name=\"11RgtANB\" /> Bersaglieri battalions created during the reform were named, with two exceptions, for battles in which Bersaglieri units had distinguished themselves: the 27th Bersaglieri Battalion was named for its defense of Hill 144 in [[Jamiano]] in 1917.\n\n=== 1992-onwards ===\n[[File:Italian Army - 11th Bersaglieri Regiment war flag at the 66th National Rally of the Bersaglieri 2018.png|thumb|right|11th Bersaglieri Regiment war flag at the 66th National Rally of the Bersaglieri]]\nOn 30 September 1992 the 27th Bersaglieri Battalion \"Jamiano\" entered the re-established 11th Bersaglieri Regiment in [[Aviano]].<ref name=\"11RgtANB\" /> On 21 November 1992 the 11th Bersaglieri Regiment moved to Orcenico Superiore, where on 18 April 1997, the 27th Bersaglieri Battalion was renamed [[11th Bersaglieri Battalion \"Caprera\"]],<ref name=\"11BersSto\" /> reunting all traditions and awards bestowed to the 11th Bersaglieri Regiment and its battalions in one unit, and gaining the tradition of the [[182nd Armored Infantry Regiment \"Garibaldi\"]] to wear the red tie with the formal uniform.<ref name=\"11RgtANB\" />\n\nIn the night of 6 April 2004, during the 11th Bersaglieri Regiment's service in Iraq as part of [[Operation Ancient Babylon]], the forces of [[Muqtada al-Sadr]]'s [[Peace Companies|Mahdi Army]] occupied the three main bridges in [[Nasiriyah]]. Three companies of the 11th Regiment, one squadron of the [[Regiment \"Savoia Cavalleria\" (3rd)]], and some logistical units of the [[132nd Armored Brigade \"Ariete\"]] engaged in an 18-hours long firefight with the rebel forces.<ref name=\"MessaggeroVeneto15May04\">{{cite news|title=Insurrezione a Nassiriya, fuoco sugli italiani - Messaggero Veneto|url=http://ricerca.gelocal.it/messaggeroveneto/archivio/messaggeroveneto/2004/05/15/NZ_03_SEB2.html?ref=search|accessdate=11 October 2017|work=Archivio - Messaggero Veneto|date=15 May 2004|language=it|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171012044116/http://ricerca.gelocal.it/messaggeroveneto/archivio/messaggeroveneto/2004/05/15/NZ_03_SEB2.html?ref=search|archive-date=2017-10-12|url-status=live}}</ref> For retaking the three bridges the 11th Bersaglieri Regiment was decorated with a [[War Cross for Military Valor]] in 2008.\n\n== Commanders ==\n* Colonel Giuseppe Barbiani (24 May - 1 December 1915);\n* Colonel Giovanni Beruto, (3 December 1915 - 13 January 1917);\n* Lieutenant Colonel Giovanni Capoani (19 January 1917 - 15 February 1917);\n* Colonel Gino Graziani (10 March 1917 - end of hostilities);\n* Colonel Vincenzo Robertiello;\n* Colonel Guglielmo Mingo;\n* Colonel Michele Adabbo;\n* Colonel Lalli (1943);\n* Colonel Alessandro Guarisco;<ref name=\"MessaggeroVeneto11Feb06\">{{cite news|title=Cambio di comando all'11\u00ba reggimento bersaglieri - Messaggero Veneto|url=http://ricerca.gelocal.it/messaggeroveneto/archivio/messaggeroveneto/2006/02/11/PN_15_DTD7.html|accessdate=11 October 2017|work=Archivio - Messaggero Veneto|date=11 February 2006|language=it|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171011130308/http://ricerca.gelocal.it/messaggeroveneto/archivio/messaggeroveneto/2006/02/11/PN_15_DTD7.html|archive-date=2017-10-11|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Colonel Michele Cittadella;<ref name=\"MessaggeroVeneto11Feb06\" />\n* Colonel Fabio Polli;\n* Colonel Salvatore Daniele Patan\u00e8 (2010-2011);\n* Colonel Alfonso Cornacchia (2011-2013);<ref name=\"MessaggeroVeneto5Oct13\">{{cite news|title=Cornacchia passa a Dess\u00ec il comando della Leccis|url=http://messaggeroveneto.gelocal.it/udine/cronaca/2013/10/05/news/cornacchia-passa-a-dessi-il-comando-della-leccis-foto-1.7867648|accessdate=11 October 2017|work=Messaggero Veneto|date=5 October 2013|language=it|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171011072621/http://messaggeroveneto.gelocal.it/udine/cronaca/2013/10/05/news/cornacchia-passa-a-dessi-il-comando-della-leccis-foto-1.7867648|archive-date=2017-10-11|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Colonel Eugenio Dess\u00ec (2013-2015);<ref name=\"Gazzettino25Jul15\">{{cite news|title=Brigata Ariete, cambio al vertice  del reggimento dei bersaglieri|url=http://www.ilgazzettino.it/pay/pordenone_pay/brigata_ariete_cambio_al_vertice_reggimento_bersaglieri-1160763.html|accessdate=11 October 2017|work=Il Gazzettino|date=25 July 2015|language=Italian|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171011073337/http://www.ilgazzettino.it/pay/pordenone_pay/brigata_ariete_cambio_al_vertice_reggimento_bersaglieri-1160763.html|archive-date=2017-10-11|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Colonel Alessandro Colaiacomo (2015\u2013present).<ref name=\"Gazzettino25Jul15\" />\n\n== Current Structure ==\nAs of 2019 the 11th Bersaglieri Regiment consists of:\n\n* [[File:CoA mil ITA rgt bersaglieri 11.png|30px]] '''Regimental Command''', in [[Zoppola|Orcenico Superiore]]\n** Command and Logistic Support Company \"Sciara Sciat\"\n** '''11th Bersaglieri Battalion \"[[Caprera]]\"'''\n*** 1st Fusiliers Company \"Jamiano\"\n*** 2nd Fusiliers Company \"San Michele\"\n*** 3rd Fusiliers Company \"Nasiriyya\"\n*** Maneuver Support Company \"Assaba\"\n\nThe Command and Logistic Support Company fields the following platoons: [[Command and control|C3 Platoon]], [[Materiel|Transport and Materiel Platoon]], [[Military medicine|Medical Platoon]], and [[Military commissariat|Commissariat Platoon]]. The regiment is equipped with tracked [[Dardo IFV|Dardo]] [[infantry fighting vehicles]]. The Maneuver Support Company is equipped with [[M106 mortar carrier|M106 120mm mortar carriers]] and Dardo IFVs with [[Spike (missile)|Spike LR]] [[anti-tank guided missiles]].\n\n== Uniform ==\nIn order to display the lineage of the 182nd Armored Infantry Regiment \"Garibaldi\", soldiers of the 11th Bersaglieri Battalion \"Caprera\" wear the red tie.<ref name=\"11BersSto\" />\n\n== Notable members ==\nFrom 13 September 1915 to 28 December 1918, [[Benito Mussolini]] served in the 11th Regiment.<ref name=\"ArchivioMussolini\">{{cite web|last1=Scarpellini|first1=Fulco|title=Copia del Foglio Matricolare di Benito Mussolini|url=http://www.larchivio.com/xoom/matricolare.htm|website=www.larchivio.com|accessdate=10 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170927034627/http://www.larchivio.com/xoom/matricolare.htm|archive-date=2017-09-27|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Bersaglieri]]\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.esercito.difesa.it/organizzazione/capo-di-sme/Comando-Forze-Operative-Nord/Divisione-Vittorio-Veneto/Brigata-Corazzata-Ariete/11-Reggimento-Bersaglieri Italian Army Website: 11th Bersaglieri Regiment]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|1}}\n\n{{Italian Army}}\n{{Italian Army Bersaglieri Regiments}}\n\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 1883]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations disestablished in 1943]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 1992]]\n[[Category:Regiments of Italy in World War I]]\n[[Category:Regiments of Italy in World War II]]\n[[Category:Bersaglieri Regiments of Italy]]\n", "name_user": "Dan Koehl", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: particiapted \u2192 participated", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/11th_Bersaglieri_Regiment"}
{"title_page": "Rathvilly (barony)", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n<!-- See Template:Infobox settlement for additional fields and descriptions -->\n| name                    = Rathvilly\n| native_name             = <small>''R\u00e1th Bhile'' ([[Irish language|Irish]])</small><ref name=\"Logainm\"/>\n| settlement_type         = [[Barony (Ireland)|Barony]]\n| image_skyline           = Rathvilly (Barony).png\n| imagesize               = 200px\n| image_alt               = \n| image_caption           = \n| image_map               = \n| map_alt                 = \n| map_caption             = \n| subdivision_type        = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n| subdivision_name        = [[Republic of Ireland]]\n| subdivision_type1       = [[Provinces of Ireland|Province]]\n| subdivision_name1       =  [[Leinster]]\n| subdivision_type2       = [[Counties of Ireland|County]]\n| subdivision_name2       =  [[County Carlow|Carlow]]\n| area_magnitude          = \n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_total_km2          = \n| area_total_sq_mi        = \n| area_land_km2           = 181.32\n| area_land_sq_mi         = \n| area_water_km2          = \n| area_water_sq_mi        = \n| area_water_percent      = \n| area_note               = \n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_m             = \n| elevation_ft            = \n}}\n\n'''Rathvilly''' ({{Lang-ga|R\u00e1th Bhile}}<ref name=\"Logainm\"/>) is a [[Barony (Ireland)|barony]] in [[County Carlow]], [[Republic of Ireland]].\n\n==Etymology==\nRathvilly barony takes its name from the village of [[Rathvilly]], which derive from the [[Irish language]] ''R\u00e1th Bhile'', meaning \"[[Ringfort|rath]] of the sacred tree\".<ref name=\"Logainm\"/>\n\n==Location==\n\nRathvilly is found in northeast [[County Carlow]]. It contains the rivers [[River Slaney|Slaney]] and [[River Derreen|Derreen]].\n\nRathvilly barony is bordered by the following baronies: to the west by [[Carlow (barony)|Carlow]]; to the south by [[Forth (County Carlow barony)|Forth]]; to the north by [[Upper Talbotstown]]; to the east by [[Ballinacor South]]; to the southeast by [[Shillelagh (barony)|Shillelagh]]; and to the northwest by [[Kilkea and Moone]].\n\n==History==\nIn the 5th century, Crimthan, [[King of Leinster]], lived at Rathvilly. The territory was that of the U\u00ed Felmelda Tuaid, a [[U\u00ed Cheinnselaig]] sept descended from Feidlimidh son of Enna Ceansalagh and brother of Crimthan. The MacKeoghs here were chief [[bard]]s of the Kings of Leinster. An O'Neill family was cantered here.<ref name=\"Rootweb\"/>\n\n==List of settlements==\nBelow is a list of settlements in Rathvilly barony:\n*[[Clonmore, County Carlow|Clonmore]]\n*[[Hacketstown]]\n*Rathvilly\n*[[Tullow]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|\n<ref name=\"Logainm\">[http://www.logainm.ie/en/344 Logainm] Irish Place Name Database - Rathvilly</ref>\n<ref name=\"Rootweb\">[http://www.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~irlcar2/parish.htm Rootsweb] - Roman Catholic Parishes of County Carlow</ref>\n}}\n\n{{County Carlow}}\n\n[[Category:Baronies of County Carlow]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n<!-- See Template:Infobox settlement for additional fields and descriptions -->\n| name                    = Rathvilly\n| native_name             = <small>''R\u00e1th Bhile'' ([[Irish language|Irish]])</small><ref name=\"Logainm\"/>\n| settlement_type         = \n| image_skyline           = \n| imagesize               = \n| image_alt               = \n| image_caption           = \n| image_map               = \n| map_alt                 = \n| map_caption             = \n| subdivision_type        = [[List of sovereign states|Sovereign state]]\n| subdivision_name        = [[Republic of Ireland]]\n| subdivision_type1       = [[Counties of Ireland|County]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[County Carlow|Carlow]]\n| area_magnitude          = \n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_total_km2          = 181.32\n| area_total_sq_mi        = 70.01\n| area_land_km2           = \n| area_land_sq_mi         = \n| area_water_km2          = \n| area_water_sq_mi        = \n| area_water_percent      = \n| area_note               = \n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_m             = \n| elevation_ft            = \n}}\n\n'''Rathvilly''' ({{Lang-ga|R\u00e1th Bhile}}<ref name=\"Logainm\"/>) is a [[Barony (Ireland)|barony]] in [[County Carlow]], [[Republic of Ireland]].\n\n==Etymology==\nRathvilly barony takes its name from the village of [[Rathvilly]], which derive from the [[Irish language]] ''R\u00e1th Bhile'', meaning \"[[Ringfort|rath]] of the sacred tree\".<ref name=\"Logainm\"/>\n\n==Location==\n\nRathvilly is found in northeast [[County Carlow]]. It contains the rivers [[River Slaney|Slaney]] and [[River Derreen|Derreen]].\n\nRathvilly barony is bordered by the following baronies: to the west by [[Carlow (barony)|Carlow]]; to the south by [[Forth (County Carlow barony)|Forth]]; to the north by [[Upper Talbotstown]]; to the east by [[Ballinacor South]]; to the southeast by [[Shillelagh (barony)|Shillelagh]]; and to the northwest by [[Kilkea and Moone]].\n\n==History==\nIn the 5th century, Crimthan, [[King of Leinster]], lived at Rathvilly. The territory was that of the U\u00ed Felmelda Tuaid, a [[U\u00ed Cheinnselaig]] sept descended from Feidlimidh son of Enna Ceansalagh and brother of Crimthan. The MacKeoghs here were chief [[bard]]s of the Kings of Leinster. An O'Neill family was cantered here.<ref name=\"Rootweb\"/>\n\n==List of settlements==\nBelow is a list of settlements in Rathvilly barony:\n*[[Clonmore, County Carlow|Clonmore]]\n*[[Hacketstown]]\n*Rathvilly\n*[[Tullow]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|\n<ref name=\"Logainm\">[http://www.logainm.ie/en/344 Logainm] Irish Place Name Database - Rathvilly</ref>\n<ref name=\"Rootweb\">[http://www.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~irlcar2/parish.htm Rootsweb] - Roman Catholic Parishes of County Carlow</ref>\n}}\n\n{{County Carlow}}\n\n[[Category:Baronies of County Carlow]]\n", "name_user": "Jacobfrid", "label": "safe", "comment": "add map", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rathvilly_(barony)"}
{"title_page": "Aircel", "text_new": "{{About|the mobile network operator|the comic book company|Aircel Comics|other uses|Air cell (disambiguation){{!}}Air cell}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=July 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Aircel Ltd.\n| logo = Aircel Logo.svg\n| logo_size = \n| logo_alt = \n| logo_caption = \n| logo_padding = \n| image = \n| image_size = \n| image_alt = \n| image_caption = \n| former_name = \n| type = [[Privately held company|Private]]<ref name= \"About Aircel\">{{cite web|url=http://www.aircel.com/AircelWar/images?url=/ucmaircel/groups/public/documents/webasset/faq-pdf.pdf|title=FAQ|access-date=1 July 2018}}</ref>\n| industry = [[Telecommunications]]\n| genre = \n| fate = Bankrupt\n| founded = [[Tiruvannamalai]], Tamilnadu and Registered at  [[Coimbatore]], [[Tamil Nadu]], India ({{Start date|1999}})<ref name= \"About Aircel\"/>\n| founder = Chinnakannan Sivasankaran\n| defunct = {{End date|df=yes|2018|02|28}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Aircel goes bankrupt, becomes fourth telecom player to bow out as cut-throat price war takes toll |url=https://www.businesstoday.in/sectors/telecom/aircel-bankruptcy-telecom-sector-nclt-numbers-insolvency/story/271714.html |website=Business Today |accessdate=1 July 2018}}</ref>\n| hq_location = Opus Centre, 47, Central Road, MIDC, [[Andheri]]\n| hq_location_city = [[Mumbai]], [[Maharashtra]]\n| hq_location_country = India<ref>{{cite web |title=Contact Us |url=http://www.aircel.com/AircelWar/appmanager/aircel/ap?_nfpb=true&_pageLabel=customercare_contactus_page |website=Aircel |accessdate=1 July 2018}}</ref>\n| num_locations = \n| num_locations_year = <!-- Year of num_locations data (if known) -->\n| area_served = <!-- or: | areas_served = -->\n| key_people = \n| products = \n| brands = \n| production = \n| production_year = <!-- Year of production data (if known) -->\n| services = [[Mobile telephony]], [[wireless broadband]]\n| revenue = {{profit}} [[US$]] 1.159 billion (2012)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://voicendata.ciol.com/content/top_stories/vnd100_2012vol-II/112072429.asp |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130119074204/http://voicendata.ciol.com/content/top_stories/vnd100_2012vol-II/112072429.asp |url-status=dead |archive-date=19 January 2013 |publisher=Voice & Data |title=Aircel: Banking on the Future |date=24 July 2012 }}</ref>\n| revenue_year = <!-- Year of revenue data (if known) -->\n| operating_income = \n| income_year = <!-- Year of operating_income data (if known) -->\n| net_income = <!-- or: | profit = -->\n| net_income_year = <!-- or: | profit_year = --><!-- Year of net_income/profit data (if known) -->\n| assets = \n| assets_year = <!-- Year of assets data (if known) -->\n| equity = \n| equity_year = <!-- Year of equity data (if known) -->\n| owners = [[Maxis Communications|Maxis]] (74%)<ref name=maxisshare>{{cite web|url=http://biz.thestar.com.my/news/story.asp?file=/2009/8/29/business/4598603&sec=business |title=The Star - Business - Maxis owns 74% of Aircel |publisher=Biz.thestar.com.my |date=29 August 2009 |accessdate=28 June 2012}}</ref> <br> [[Apollo Hospitals]] (Sindya Securities and Investments 26%)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/companies/apollo-group-prathap-c-reddy-have-no-investment-in-aircel/article2227232.ece|title=Apollo group, Prathap C. Reddy have no investment in Aircel}}</ref>\n| members = \n| members_year = <!-- Year of members data (if known) -->\n| num_employees = \n| num_employees_year = <!-- Year of num_employees data (if known) -->\n| parent = \n| divisions = \n| subsid = \n| module = <!-- Used to embed other templates -->\n| website = {{URL|http://aircel.com/}}\n| footnotes = \n}}\n\n'''Aircel Ltd.''' was an  [[Mobile network operators of India|Indian mobile network operator]] headquartered in [[Mumbai]] that offered voice and [[2G]] and [[3G]] data services. [[Maxis Communications]] held a 74% stake and Sindya Securities and Investments held the remaining 26%.<ref name=maxisshare /> Aircel was founded by Chinnakannan Sivasankaran and commenced operations in [[Tamil Nadu]] in 1999. It was once a market leader in [[Tamil Nadu]] and had considerable presence in [[Odisha]], [[Assam]] and North-East [[telecom circle]]s. [[2G]] and [[3G]] Services including voice were shut down in all circles due to failure in merge with [[Reliance Communications]].\n\n==History==\nAircel was founded by Chinnakannan Sivasankaran from [[Kovilur, Tiruvannamalai|Kovilur]], [[Tiruvannamalai]] district and started its operations in the [[Tamil Nadu]] telecom circle in 1999.<ref name=\"aircelbg\">{{cite web|url=http://www.lightreading.in/document.asp?site=lrindia&doc_id=226988&page_number=1|title=Aicel: What the future holds|date=15 September 2012|publisher=Light Reading India|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130217234051/http://www.lightreading.in/document.asp?site=lrindia&doc_id=226988&page_number=1|archive-date=17 February 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It became the leading operator in Tamil Nadu and one of the fastest growing mobile operators in India.<ref name=\"aircelbg\"/> Malaysian telecom company [[Maxis Communications]] bought a 74% stock in the company from Sivasankaran in 2005. The remaining 26% stock is held by Sindya Securities and Investments promoted by Suneeta Reddy, Managing Director of [[Apollo Hospitals]]. In 2012, as a part of a major re-organization in its operations, the company scaled down its operations in five [[telecom circle]]s, namely [[Madhya Pradesh]], [[Gujarat]], [[Haryana]], [[Kerala]] and [[Punjab, India|Punjab]]. In April 2015, Aircel relaunched its service in [[Kerala]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.dnaindia.com/money/report_after-uninor-aircel-to-hang-up-in-5-circles_1752067| publisher=[[Daily News and Analysis]]| title=Aircel to withdraw from 5 circles| date=13 October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tech/news/telecom/Aircel-to-cut-600-jobs/articleshow/16794330.cms |work=[[Times of India]] |date=13 October 2012 |title=Aircel to cut 600 jobs}}</ref> On 14 September 2016, [[Reliance Communications]] and Aircel announced the merger of their mobile network operations. Following the merger, the joint entity was expected to become India's fourth largest telecom operator in term of consumer base and revenues.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Pandey|first1=Piyush|title=RCom-Aircel merger a strong challenger to Idea Cellular|url=http://www.thehindu.com/business/Industry/RCom-Aircel-merger-a-strong-challenger-to-Idea-Cellular/article14637988.ece|accessdate=9 January 2018|work=[[The Hindu]]|date=14 September 2016}}</ref> A year later, however, both the companies called off the deal citing regulatory and legal issues.<ref>{{cite news|title=RCom, Aircel hang up on merger plans|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/info-tech/rcom-aircel-hang-up-on-merger-plans/article9883410.ece|accessdate=9 January 2018|work=[[Business Line]]|date=1 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nAircel had planned to shut down its operations in unprofitable circles including, Gujarat, Maharashtra, Haryana, Himachal Pradesh, Madhya Pradesh and Uttar Pradesh (West) from 30 January 2018.<ref>{{cite web|title=Aircel to shut operations in six circles from January 30|url=http://www.moneycontrol.com/news/business/aircel-to-shut-operations-in-six-circles-from-january-30-2465863.html|publisher=[[Moneycontrol.com]]|accessdate=3 January 2018}}</ref> The [[Telecom Regulatory Authority of India]] (TRAI) asked Aircel to report the number of subscribers who have ported out from Aircel in these six circles. In cases, where the porting process could not be completed TRAI has asked the reasons for it.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Pandey|first1=Navadha|title=Trai directs Aircel to submit a report on subscriber port-out in 6 circles|url=http://www.livemint.com/Industry/t3UQ3i4Civ6arkM7hEO57O/Trai-directs-Aircel-to-submit-report-on-subscriber-portout.html|accessdate=9 January 2018|work=[[Mint (newspaper)|Mint]]|date=21 December 2017|location=New Delhi}}</ref> After the failed merger deal with Reliance, Aircel had considered merging with [[Bharti Airtel]], whose chairman [[Sunil Mittal]] had stated in November 2017, that Airtel \"was open to acquisition talks\". {{As of|December 2017}}, Aircel was under a debt of around {{INRConvert|16000|c}}.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kurup|first1=Rajesh|title=Aircel looking at ways to stay afloat|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/info-tech/aircel-looking-at-ways-to-stay-afloat/article9983369.ece|accessdate=9 January 2018|work=[[Business Line]]|date=5 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Services==\n\n===3G===\nOn 19 May 2010, the 3G spectrum auction in India ended. Aircel paid {{INR}} 65 billion for spectrum in 13 circles: [[Andhra Pradesh]], [[Assam]], [[Bihar]], [[Jammu & Kashmir]], [[Karnataka]], [[Kerala]], [[Kolkata]], [[Madhya Pradesh]] and [[Chhattisgarh]], [[Northeast India|North East]], [[Odisha]], [[Punjab, India|Punjab]], [[Tamil Nadu]], [[Uttar Pradesh|UP East]] and [[West Bengal]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.medianama.com/2010/05/223-3g-auction-india-ends-provisional-winners/ |title=India's 3G Auction Ends; Operator And Circle-Wise Results |accessdate=21 May 2013|date=19 May 2010 }}</ref> It paid US$1.44 billion ({{INR}} 79.1 billion) for the 3G spectrum.<ref name=\"aircelbg\"/> The company, {{as of|November 2012|lc=y}} had about 5 million 3G customers. Following the key players in 3G, Aircel also slashed its 3G tariff.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tech/news/telecom/Aircel-cuts-3G-tariffs-in-India/articleshow/13841425.cms |title=Aircel cuts 3G tariffs in India |date=5 June 2012 |accessdate=21 May 2013 |work=The Times Of India}}</ref> In 2011, Aircel became the launch partner for Apple [[iPhone 4]] along with [[Bharti Airtel]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://site2preview.com/aircel2010_new/ver1/iphone4/i-phone-LP.html |title=\u2022 Aircel \u2022 |publisher=Site2preview.com |accessdate=6 July 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120324140302/http://site2preview.com/aircel2010_new/ver1/iphone4/i-phone-LP.html |archive-date=24 March 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===4G===\nIn June 2010, Aircel paid {{INR}} 34.38&nbsp;billion for acquiring wireless broadband spectrum in eight circles: [[Andhra Pradesh]], [[Assam]], [[Bihar]] and [[Jharkhand]], [[Jammu & Kashmir]], North East, [[Odisha]], [[Tamil Nadu]] and [[West Bengal]].<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.medianama.com/2010/06/223-indias-broadband-wireless-auction-ends-operator-circlewise-results/ |title=India's Broadband Wireless Auction Ends; Operator & Circlewise Results |author= Pahwa, Nikhil |date=11 June 2010 |work= Medianama |location= Delhi |accessdate=21 May 2013}}</ref> Aircel launched 4G services in Tamil Nadu and Jammu & Kashmir in August 2014, becoming the only private telecom operator to offer all the three existing technologies of 2G, 3G and 4G in these markets.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tech/tech-news/Aircel-launches-4G-services-in-Tamil-Nadu-Jammu-Kashmir/articleshow/40364889.cms |title= Aircel launches 4G services in Tamil Nadu, Jammu & Kashmir |publisher= Times Of India |accessdate=18 August 2014|date= 18 August 2014 }}</ref> Chinese equipment maker [[ZTE]] announced on 30 December 2013, that it had won a contract to deploy a 4G broadband network based on LTE technology for Aircel. The LTE network will be launched in Tamil Nadu and will be expanded later to other circles.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/industry-and-economy/info-tech/zte-bags-4g-contract-from-aircel/article5518356.ece |title=ZTE bags 4G contract from Aircel |work= The Hindu BusinessLine |location= Chennai |date=30 December 2013 |accessdate=24 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tech/tech-news/telecom/ZTE-to-deploy-4G-LTE-network-for-Aircel/articleshow/28136544.cms |title=Aircel selects ZTE for 4G network rollout |work=The Times of India |location= Mumbai |date=30 December 2013 |accessdate=24 January 2014}}</ref> On 16 July 2014, it launched 4G services in four circles [[Andhra Pradesh]], [[Assam]], [[Bihar]] and [[Odisha]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Aircel launches First 4G Mobile Services in Bihar|url=http://news.biharprabha.com/2014/07/aircel-first-to-launch-4g-mobile-services-in-bihar/|work=IANS|publisher=news.biharprabha.com|accessdate=16 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Business Solutions===\nAircel Business Solutions (ABS), part of Aircel, sold enterprise [[solution]]s such as [[Multiprotocol Label Switching]] [[Virtual Private Network]]s (MPLS VPNs), [[Voice over Internet Protocol]] (VoIP) and managed video services on wireless platforms including WI-MAX.\n\n==Network connectivity==\nAircel offered poor network coverage in Delhi & NCR circle.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Press Trust of India|title=Call drops: TRAI to impose up to \u20b92 lakh penalty for poor service But Aircel has not improved their Network |url=http://www.livemint.com/Industry/dbzaNBToTiG6Wf1wzmxCEI/No-significant-improvement-in-call-drop-issue-Trai.html|accessdate=5 June 2016|work=[[Mint (newspaper)|Mint]]|date=15 October 2015|location=New Delhi|author1-link=Press Trust of India }}</ref> It used radio link time out technology without which the call drop rates will be significantly higher and many customers reported this.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Srivastava|first1=Moulishree|title=TRAI wants powers to impose penalties as telcos fail call drop test|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/companies/trai-wants-powers-to-impose-penalties-as-telcos-fail-call-drop-test-116060101865_1.html|accessdate=5 June 2016|work=[[Business Standard]]|date=2 June 2016}}</ref> In a 2015 survey conducted by ''[[Mint (newspaper)|Mint]]'' and InstaVaani in New Delhi, Mumbai, Bengaluru, Chennai, Hyderabad, Ahmedabad and Kolkata, it was found that Aircel offered the best service among all the telecom providers in the respective cities.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Shashidhar|first1=Karthik|last2=Ghosh|first2=Shauvik|title=India's best and worst telecom firms|url=http://www.livemint.com/Industry/ZNfBYfxV3s94qdjcptSTnM/Indias-best-and-worst-telcos.html|accessdate=5 June 2016|work=[[Mint (newspaper)|Mint]]|date=8 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Operations==\n{{As of|2017|12}}, Aircel had a subscriber base of over 84.93 million and was India's sixth-largest GSM mobile service provider.<ref name=\"Dec17\">{{cite web|url=http://www.trai.gov.in/notifications/press-release/press-release-telecom-subscription-data-28th-february-2018|title=Press release on Telecom Subscription Data as on 28th February, 2018 &#124; Telecom Regulatory Authority of India}}</ref> With presence in 22 circles, Aircel was a market leader in [[Tamil Nadu]] and had considerable presence in [[Odisha]], [[Assam]] and [[North-East India|North-East]] circles. In 2012, as a part of a major re-organization in its operations, the company scaled down its operations in five telecom circles, namely [[Madhya Pradesh]], [[Gujarat]], [[Haryana]], [[Kerala]] and [[Punjab, India|Punjab]]. In April 2015, Aircel relaunched its service in [[Kerala]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.dnaindia.com/money/report_after-uninor-aircel-to-hang-up-in-5-circles_1752067|work=[[Daily News and Analysis]] |title=Aircel to withdraw from 5 circles| date=13 October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tech/news/telecom/Aircel-to-cut-600-jobs/articleshow/16794330.cms|work=[[The Times of India]] |date=13 October 2012 |title=Aircel to cut 600 jobs}}</ref>\n\nNow Aircel is under the Corporate Insolvency Resolution Process From 12th March 2018.\n\n==Sponsorship and brand ambassadors==\nAircel was the main shirt sponsor of [[Indian Premier League]] [[cricket]] team [[Chennai Super Kings]] and [[I-League]] [[association football|football]] team [[Shillong Lajong FC]]. Aircel was also the principal sponsor for [[Atl\u00e9tico de Kolkata|Atl\u00e9tico de Kolkata FC]] who play in the [[Indian Super League]] football competition. It was also a major sponsor of the [[Chennai Open]] [[Association of Tennis Professionals|ATP]] tennis tournament and the Professional Golf Tour of India. Aircel also sponsored the Save the Tiger campaign for protecting India's tigers. The brand ambassadors of Aircel included the Indian cricket team captain [[Mahendra Singh Dhoni]] and [[Tamil cinema|Tamil]] actor [[Suriya (actor)|Suriya]]. Aircel also engaged with boxer [[Mary Kom]], [[Tamil cinema|Tamil]] actors [[Dhanush]] and [[Sameera Reddy]].<ref name=\"aircelbg3\">{{cite web| url=http://www.lightreading.in/document.asp?site=lrindia&doc_id=226988&page_number=3| title=Aicel: What the future holds (Page 3)| publisher=Light Reading India| date=15 September 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\nAircel is being investigated by [[Central Bureau of Investigation|CBI]] for alleged irregularities in the Maxis takeover. According to CBI, Aircel's previous owner C. Sivasankaran was forced to sell his stake to Maxis by the then Telecom Minister [[Dayanidhi Maran]] in 2005 in return for Maxis' investment of Rs. 5 billion in a DTH company owned by the Maran family.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/business/india-business/Marans-got-Rs-550cr-bribe-in-Aircel-Maxis-deal-CBI/articleshow/15175723.cms| publisher=[[Times of India]]| date=27 July 2012| title=Maran-Maxis deal}}</ref> There were also rumours in September 2012 that the Russian company [[Sistema]] was in talks to acquire Aircel which wasn't confirmed by either companies.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/business/india-business/Sistema-in-talks-to-acquire-Aircel/articleshow/16388282.cms| publisher=[[Times of India]]| date=14 September 2012| title=Sistema to acquire Aircel?}}</ref> Aircel was one among seven operators to receive notices from the [[Department of Telecommunications]] for not meeting [[Mobile phone radiation and health#Health hazards of base stations|radiation norms]] in their base tower stations in September 2012.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-09-14/telecom/33843566_1_radiation-norms-mobile-towers-antenna| publisher=[[Times of India]]| date=14 September 2012| title=Aircel gets DoT notice}}</ref>\nNearly nine lakh customers across India on 21 February 2018 tried to port their numbers after facing frequent call drops, amidst reports of the company facing financial distress. After several users took to Facebook and Twitter to express their fear of the company shutting down, Aircel clarified on social media that it is not closing its services and that users will be notified in advance of any such eventuality. A senior official told The Times of India, \"The systems are unable to handle the surge. However, we are not going anywhere. It is our responsibility to serve customers until the end. We are devising a way to create manual codes to facilitate the porting process.\"\nFinally most of its customers ported out since there is no network signal provided by them starting March 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/aircel-shutting-down-and-should-you-be-worried-customer-5-things-know-76864|title=Is Aircel shutting down and should you be worried as a customer? 5 things to know|date=22 February 2018|publisher=}}</ref> On 28 February 2018 Aircel filed for bankruptcy at [[National Company Law Tribunal|NCLT]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/company/corporate-trends/aircel-countrys-last-small-mobile-phone-firm-file-for-bankruptcy-today/articleshow/63110441.cms |title=Aircel, country's last small mobile phone operator, files for bankruptcy |last=Sengupta |first=Devina |date=28 February 2018 |work=The Economic Times |access-date=28 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.facebook.com/notes/aircel-india/aircel-press-release/1893902820650898/ |title=Aircel's bankruptcy note on Facebook}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Mobile network operators of India]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.aircel.com/}}\n\n{{Telecommunication companies of India}}\n\n[[Category:Telecommunications companies of India]]\n[[Category:Mobile phone companies of India]]\n[[Category:Internet service providers of India]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Indian companies established in 1999]]\n[[Category:Indian companies disestablished in 2018]]\n[[Category:Telecommunications companies established in 1999]]\n[[Category:Telecommunications companies disestablished in 2018]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the mobile network operator|the comic book company|Aircel Comics|other uses|Air cell (disambiguation){{!}}Air cell}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=July 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Aircel Ltd.\n| logo = Aircel Logo.svg\n| logo_size = \n| logo_alt = \n| logo_caption = \n| logo_padding = \n| image = \n| image_size = \n| image_alt = \n| image_caption = \n| former_name = \n| type = [[Privately held company|Private]]<ref name= \"About Aircel\">{{cite web|url=http://www.aircel.com/AircelWar/images?url=/ucmaircel/groups/public/documents/webasset/faq-pdf.pdf|title=FAQ|access-date=1 July 2018}}</ref>\n| industry = [[Telecommunications]]\n| genre = \n| fate = Bankrupt\n| founded = [[Tiruvannamalai]], Tamilnadu and Registered at  [[Coimbatore]], [[Tamil Nadu]], India ({{Start date|1999}})<ref name= \"About Aircel\"/>\n| founder = Chinnakannan Sivasankaran\n| defunct = {{End date|df=yes|2018|02|28}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Aircel goes bankrupt, becomes fourth telecom player to bow out as cut-throat price war takes toll |url=https://www.businesstoday.in/sectors/telecom/aircel-bankruptcy-telecom-sector-nclt-numbers-insolvency/story/271714.html |website=Business Today |accessdate=1 July 2018}}</ref>\n| hq_location = Opus Centre, 47, Central Road, MIDC, [[Andheri]]\n| hq_location_city = [[Mumbai]], [[Maharashtra]]\n| hq_location_country = India